It was useful when people started moving information online, but it's inherently flawed."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What is metadata?","timeRequired":"PT1M17S","description":"A much better way of organizing information is through the use of metadata, but what does metadata mean?"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"The power of metadata","timeRequired":"PT3M","description":"Check out some examples of how using metadata gives you opportunities in organizing and using your information."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Libraries often mirror existing structures","timeRequired":"PT4M3S","description":"Ineffective use of SharePoint libraries negatively impacts the experience of users. Rather than using abilities in SharePoint for organizing files, many sites simply import a complicated folder structure onto the new platform. This doesn't fix anything. It just moves the problem from one place to another."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"People don’t understand version control","timeRequired":"PT5M30S","description":"SharePoint has versioning capabilities. If you're saving files with \".v1, .v2,\" etc. extensions, you're not only creating extra work for yourself, you're creating more opportunity for error."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"People store spreadsheets rather than using lists","timeRequired":"PT3M3S","description":"SharePoint Lists can replace spreadsheets. Did you know that you can create custom lists in SharePoint that not only store data but can also perform calculations just like an Excel spreadsheet, without the need to upload and download files?"},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Understanding your data","timeRequired":"PT3M27S","description":"Develop metadata. The first step in developing a schema\"for your metadata is understanding your data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Understanding how the data is used","timeRequired":"PT3M10S","description":"Develop with results and audience in mind. When you're creating your schema, a very important question to ask is how the data needs to be used, and by whom."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Metadata structure for libraries","timeRequired":"PT2M52S","description":"Select metadata for libraries. Spreadsheets are straightforward, but how do you build a metadata schema for a library? You actually have more information to help you than you think."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Lists instead of spreadsheets","timeRequired":"PT3M20S","description":"Learn how SharePoint lists are a strong alternative to Excel spreadsheets. Spreadsheets are very familiar to people and are a good way of performing complex calculations. But often spreadsheets contain data rather than numbers, which means they can be replaced easily by lists in SharePoint."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Adding \"choice\" columns to capture metadata","timeRequired":"PT6M13S","description":"Learn how to add choice\"data type columns to a SharePoint list. Adding columns to your list lets you make space to collect the information you need. One of the most useful types of data you can collect are predefined choices."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Lookup columns","timeRequired":"PT2M55S","description":"If you use similar data in multiple places in your site, using lookup columns in your list might be a good idea. It not only makes creating lists faster but also  guarantees consistency in your metadata."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Calculating columns","timeRequired":"PT4M25S","description":"Learn how to use calculating columns. SharePoint has the ability to perform calculations, just like Excel—and just like Excel, it goes way beyond simple math."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What do lists and libraries have in common?","timeRequired":"PT2M23S","description":"Lessons you have learned about lists can apply to libraries. Libraries in SharePoint are actually lists of documents, so you already know most of what you need to work with them."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Permission protection for access and editing","timeRequired":"PT4M58S","description":"Discover the concept of protecting lists and libraries using permissions. Use SharePoint permission groups to define who has the ability to view or edit your documents, and lists, too."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Co-editing and checkout/check-in","timeRequired":"PT3M34S","description":"Discover SharePoint's ability to let multiple users edit files simultaneously. Letting your users co-edit files can speed up workflow, but you check-in."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Using version control instead of multiple versions","timeRequired":"PT5M22S","description":"Learn how to use SharePoint's version history. You don't need multiple versions of a document if you use SharePoint's built-in version control."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Restoring old versions","timeRequired":"PT2M48S","description":"Learn how to view and restore previous versions of a file. If you ever need an older version, it's easy to view or retrieve it."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Creating multiple views","timeRequired":"PT3M40S","description":"Learn how to create multiple views for data. One of the best things about using SharePoint for document and data storage is that it gives you the ability to create multiple views of your information. Not only that—but you can stage those views in multiple places on your site and even tailor access to them, based on your users' permissions levels."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Sorting and grouping results in a view","timeRequired":"PT3M49S","description":"Find out how to sort and group results in a view. Views allow you to sort on multiple levels of data. Not only that, you can group data by type, creating an almost folder-like appearance without the drawbacks of folders."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Totaling and counting results in a view","timeRequired":"PT4M28S","description":"Learn how to total or count results in a view. In addition to creating calculating fields in a list, you can also perform some calculations in views."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Filtering results","timeRequired":"PT5M14S","description":"Learn how to filter view results. In addition to sorting and grouping, you can also filter views to show only a subset of records."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Staging views on pages","timeRequired":"PT3M10S","description":"Learn how to stage views on site pages. This course, from database expert Adam Wilbert, takes a deep dive into leveraging these powerful and flexible components of a SQL Server database."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What you should know","timeRequired":"PT46S","description":"To get the most out of this course, you should come prepared with a working knowledge of SQL Server and writing T-SQL commands. You should feel comfortable writing basic queries and exploring the objects that make up a relational database."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Make the most of the exercise files","timeRequired":"PT1M27S","description":"In this video, Adam walks you through the steps of obtaining the exercise files so that you can follow along with him throughout the course. Inside of the exercise files folder are subfolders for each chapter, and within those are the SQL scripts that are used to explore triggers. Adam also adds an empty database to his server to work in."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What are SQL Server triggers?","timeRequired":"PT3M37S","description":"In this video, Adam explores the role that triggers play in a SQL Server database. In this video, explore the mechanisms that cause triggers to fire and gain an understanding of the types of tasks that they can accomplish."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Two triggers types: INSTEAD OF and AFTER","timeRequired":"PT2M34S","description":"SQL Server supports two types of triggers: AFTER and INSTEAD OF. The AFTER trigger executes following the successful completion of a triggering task, and the INSTEAD OF trigger replaces the requested operation with its own. Adam explores the differences between these two fundamental types."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create a trigger to print a message","timeRequired":"PT6M17S","description":"In this video, Adam walks you through the process of writing your first trigger for SQL Server. The trigger is activated by any INSERT commands sent to a table and responds with a custom message back to the end-user."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Timestamp a table modification","timeRequired":"PT5M31S","description":"One of the common uses of a trigger is to add a timestamp to indicate the last time a row’s values were modified. In this video, learn how to use an AFTER trigger to add automatic event logging right into a table row."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Firing INSTEAD OF triggers","timeRequired":"PT3M23S","description":"The INSTEAD OF trigger substitutes its own commands to execute, rather than the commands that caused it to fire. Adam shows how to leverage this type of trigger to intercept a DELETE command and rollback its transaction."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Challenge: Create a trigger","timeRequired":"PT58S","description":"For the first challenge of the course, you are tasked with creating a trigger to log when rows are added or updated in a table. This challenge builds on and reinforces the lessons learned throughout the chapter."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Solution: Create a trigger","timeRequired":"PT7M10S","description":"Adam shares his solution to the first challenge by creating three triggers on the same table. Each trigger responds to a different event; one each for INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE events. Adam’s final solution is added to the course exercise files so that you can compare your solution against his."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Read values modified by a trigger","timeRequired":"PT3M32S","description":"When a trigger fires based on a DML statement, the rows that are inserted, updated, or deleted are accessible in two temporary tables. In this video, Adam shows how to view the contents of the inserted and deleted tables to see how they can be used during the execution of the trigger."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Using the inserted logical table","timeRequired":"PT5M58S","description":"The inserted logical table contains values that are added or updated by a trigger. Using these values, database developers can extend their triggers to make use of the new data in their code. In this video, Adam shares a technique for adding additional information to inserted data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Using the deleted logical table","timeRequired":"PT3M50S","description":"The deleted logical table contains values that are removed from a table during a DELETE or UPDATE event. In this video, Adam shows how to pull values from the deleted table to create an archive of old and discarded data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Triggers on CREATE, ALTER, or DROP","timeRequired":"PT2M47S","description":"Data Definition Language triggers are fired by CREATE, ALTER, DROP, GRANT, REVOKE, or DENY commands. In this video, Adam shares links to the official documentation that outlines all of the possible triggering events or group events supported by SQL Server."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Rollback database modifications","timeRequired":"PT3M36S","description":"Using a database level trigger, developers can create a system that automatically rolls back any transactions that would modify the structure of a database. Watching the instructor's prior LinkedIn Learning course called Designing Data Governance is not required but strongly encouraged since this course content builds on the principles covered throughout that other course."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Manage your data as a product","timeRequired":"PT2M24S","description":"Data has historically been managed as a service. This lesson teaches you how to scale high-quality data through your organization by managing it as a product for others to use and benefit from."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Choose a high-priority project","timeRequired":"PT1M37S","description":"Data teams often fail because they don't link their efforts back to business strategies. To get the sponsorship needed for your work to thrive, choose a use case that C-suite leadership really cares about."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Do a data audit","timeRequired":"PT2M47S","description":"Accurately assessing your current data quality, compliance, and architecture is the first step towards designing a more data-driven future."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create a current-state process map","timeRequired":"PT2M16S","description":"Process maps show each step needed to complete an essential business process, including which systems each step occurs in and who's responsible for them. This is an essential step to improve your data QA."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Define data quality","timeRequired":"PT2M32S","description":"What does data quality look like? This lesson shares how to select success metrics that let your data teams know when data falls short, and where it is within your pipeline."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Write a roadmap for data product delivery","timeRequired":"PT2M1S","description":"Shepherding your data as a product helps you view data as an asset with its own value and lifecycle. This lesson covers the basics of a roadmap—including a high-level execution strategy marked by key tasks and milestones—to integrate data QA throughout your chosen project."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Write data requirements for your roadmap","timeRequired":"PT1M51S","description":"Bringing your data product to life demands a process to find, validate, and ingest the specific data needed. This lesson shows how to write requirements to ensure that you get the right, high-quality data for your project."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Confirm your data's source system(s)","timeRequired":"PT2M17S","description":"When data quality problems exist, they often start in the source system. This lesson covers how to trace data back to its origin location."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Establish the right data system integrations","timeRequired":"PT2M34S","description":"If you're like most organizations, you have Frankendata which lives on disparate systems that don't integrate with each other. This lesson covers how to learn where the data you need for your project lives so you can connect the right systems together."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Define your source data's minimum acceptance criteria (MAC)","timeRequired":"PT1M52S","description":"What are the Pass/Fail conditions for your data that lets data teams know what deserves a second look? This lesson shows you how to write them."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Set up data lineage tracking","timeRequired":"PT3M2S","description":"Data lineage tracks each data point over time, from its source system to which pipelines it appears in. It's an essential part of building ethical AI that passes compliance. This lesson shows you how to set it up."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Define levels of access per user","timeRequired":"PT2M36S","description":"Not all users should access all of your data. This lesson shows you how to define levels of access to data based on user roles that are relevant to your project."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Draft a to-be process map","timeRequired":"PT2M33S","description":"Remember that as-is process map you made earlier in this course? Now, it's time to draft a to-be process map showing your desired end state for data tasks, systems, and ownership."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Define areas of data transformation","timeRequired":"PT2M35S","description":"What does it look like to change your data's format, structure, or values? This lesson shows you how to do data transformation, and how to show where it occurs throughout your pipelines."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Choose some super users to validate your product","timeRequired":"PT1M44S","description":"Who's your audience for this data product? Finding, engaging, and including a group of super users in usability testing increases the chance of high adoption during deployment."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Give your data team room to fail","timeRequired":"PT2M56S","description":"Introducing this much change to your data infrastructure always carries risk. This lesson shares why you should build a sandbox environment that's separate from dev, staging, or production where your team can experiment with new tech while minimizing risk."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Make a plan to govern data throughout the full lifecycle","timeRequired":"PT2M38S","description":"Data products don't have fixed start and end dates. This lesson shares why your QA plan must run through post-deployment and manage data as an ongoing lifecycle."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Practice data mesh design principles","timeRequired":"PT3M29S","description":"Data mesh helps you keep data organized within your architecture. This lesson explains what it is, and how to set it up according to domains."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Automate federated data QA standards","timeRequired":"PT2M12S","description":"Data mesh architecture uses federated principles to operate. This lesson shares what that means, and how to measure success."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Execute data security standards","timeRequired":"PT2M25S","description":"It's important to keep data safe at all stages of your product lifecycle. This lesson shares how to put your data security standards into practice."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Make a traceability matrix","timeRequired":"PT2M45S","description":"A traceability matrix helps you prioritize your data security requirements. This lesson shows you how to write one."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Scale and automate your data QA standards","timeRequired":"PT3M1S","description":"To ensure that your data QA stays high, you need to monitor it at scale. This lesson explains how to automate that process so you stay on top of it while gaining time back."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Use feature stores to prevent data drift","timeRequired":"PT2M49S","description":"Data drift results when your data quality decreases over time, resulting in a data product that decreases in quality. This lesson explains how using feature stores can prevent data drift."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Ship new data as deployable units","timeRequired":"PT2M10S","description":"Shipping data as deployable units helps data engineers group data, metadata, and relevant files together. This lesson shows you how to set it up from within your data mesh architecture."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Track ongoing regulation changes","timeRequired":"PT3M10S","description":"Regulation changes like GDPR and CCPA mean that companies can't wing data compliance like they used to. This course's final lesson covers the importance of monitoring your data environment to ensure compliance via data stewardship."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Continuing your learning journey in the data quality","timeRequired":"PT1M10S","description":"Data QA has more in common with supply chains than code. In this video, learn how this option provides for quick migration, but at additional infrastructure cost."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Option 2: Replatforming databases","timeRequired":"PT3M25S","description":"The second migration option is to replatform your database to a cloud-native solution while still maintaining your source database engine. In this video, learn what replatforming is, including its benefits and disadvantages."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Option 3: Refactoring databases","timeRequired":"PT5M50S","description":"The third migration option is to refactor your databases to use entirely cloud-driven technologies. In this video, learn about that step."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Step 2: Schema conversion","timeRequired":"PT1M","description":"The second step in modernizing your databases is to convert the database schema from its original form into a schema that works with the technologies of the destination platform. In this video, learn about that step."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Step 3: Data migration","timeRequired":"PT1M37S","description":"The third and final step in modernizing your databases is to migrate the data to its new home, which may also include syncing the data between locations while work is ongoing. In this video, learn about that step."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Database assessments","timeRequired":"PT1M27S","description":"Before you can start migrating your databases, you need to understand your current state and create migration plans. This is done as part of a database migration assessment process. The assessment process involves analysis of your current database portfolio and the creation of migration plans. In this video, learn what the goals of database assessments are and the different steps involved."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Assessment steps","timeRequired":"PT3M45S","description":"There are several steps you have to perform as part of your database modernization and migration assessment. These include steps to understand the current state, the drivers for modernization, budget for migration, and desired target state. In this video, learn what to look for when performing your assessments."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Assessment tools","timeRequired":"PT5M42S","description":"Executing large-scale database modernization and migration assessments can be a difficult, error-prone, and time-consuming process when done manually. Luckily there are several tools you can use to accelerate and automate the process. In this video, explore three tools that can be used to accelerate your assessment process: migVisor by EPAM, Amazon SCT, and Ora2Pg."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Plan your migration","timeRequired":"PT7M42S","description":"There are several clearly defined steps you should follow when planning your database modernization journey. In this video, learn what you should account for when running your migration assessment when it comes to analyzing your current state, what to look for when planning your target state, and how to account for the migration plan in between."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Database schema conversion","timeRequired":"PT4M29S","description":"Converting your database schema between your source and target database engines is one of the more challenging and complicated tasks. In this video, learn about the conceptual ideas behind schema to schema conversion including migration of stored procedures and the challenges that may pose."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Automatic schema conversion","timeRequired":"PT3M24S","description":"There are two ways to migrate a database schema and its objects from one database technology to another: either automatically using tools or manually using database experts. In this video, learn the differences between automatic and manual schema conversion, and why a mix of both is usually the required path moving forward."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Examples of schema conversion tools","timeRequired":"PT6M2S","description":"In this video, learn about two of the most well-known tools for automating your schema conversion process and the advantages of each."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Application data access layer","timeRequired":"PT4M57S","description":"In addition to the database schema changes, which will be required when modernization databases, you also need to perform some changes to your application’s data access layer. Learn about functions, triggers, Ledger, Python, and more in this comprehensive course from database expert Adam Wilbert."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"What you should know","timeRequired":"PT2M3S","description":"To get the most out of this course, you should come prepared with a working knowledge of SQL Server and writing T-SQL commands. You should feel comfortable writing basic queries and understand the objects that make up a relational database."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Getting the most from the exercise files","timeRequired":"PT3M40S","description":"In this video, Adam walks you through the steps of obtaining the exercise files so that you can follow along with him throughout the course. Inside of the exercise files folder are subfolders for each section and chapter, and within those are the database scripts that will be used. The WideWorldImporters database from Microsoft is also required for this course, and Adam shows you how to obtain and install that database from a backup."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Program databases with SQL Server","timeRequired":"PT2M7S","description":"Learn about the objects and techniques you can use to automate complex routines and incorporate programming logic into your SQL Server databases."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Save a query as a view object","timeRequired":"PT5M44S","description":"View objects are generally the first object that’s added to a database after tables and relationships are created. Views combine information from different tables together and are defined with a T-SQL SELECT query. In this video, learn the benefits to end users when views are provided for common database queries."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Explore existing views","timeRequired":"PT4M8S","description":"When working with a new database, it’s important to understand which views already exist in a database and what tables they reference. In this video, learn how to locate views using the graphical interface and perform a couple of T-SQL queries against system management views to pull that information off the server."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"SCHEMABINDING a view","timeRequired":"PT6M32S","description":"Modifications to the structure of a table after a view is created can break the view. Database developers can prevent this from accidentally happening by SCHEMABINDING the view to the table. In this video, learn how the WITH SCHEMABINDING option locks the two objects together so that disruptive changes cannot be made to the table."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Leverage view objects with indexes","timeRequired":"PT6M1S","description":"Adding indexes to a view can improve the query performance of a SQL Server database. With an indexed view, duplicate and denormalized data is stored in the view object, giving the query engine additional options for choosing an optimal query plan. In this video, learn how to create an index on a view."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Deterministic vs. nondeterministic functions","timeRequired":"PT6M4S","description":"The SQL Server database engine might not be able to index a view if it contains nondeterministic functions. In this video, learn the difference between deterministic and nondeterministic functions in SQL Server and how to identify which built-in functions fall into which category."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Scalar-valued user-defined functions","timeRequired":"PT6M42S","description":"User-defined functions allow database programmers to accept inputs from an end user and process those inputs in consistent and predictable ways. In this video, learn how to create functions that return single values that can be reused in a T-SQL SELECT statement."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"IF ELSE and CASE statements","timeRequired":"PT5M18S","description":"Database programmers can use several statements to control the output of their functions. In this video, learn best practices for generating and working with the digest."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Verify ledger integrity","timeRequired":"PT3M23S","description":"SQL Server 2022 includes new catalog views and stored procedures for monitoring the ledger digest for discrepancies. In this video, learn about the data management lifecycle and how it can help you keep your valuable data accessible and secure while getting the most bang for your cloud buck."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Data security in AWS","timeRequired":"PT5M11S","description":"Data security, like all security in AWS, is a partnership between you and the cloud provider. In this video, learn about all the ways that AWS makes your data safe—and understand where your responsibilities begin."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Regulatory compliance and AWS","timeRequired":"PT4M39S","description":"AWS takes the confusion out of meeting compliance in the cloud by clearly detailing the ways in which the individual service offerings do and do not adhere to numerous compliance frameworks. In this video, find out how to access this crucial information as you start your cloud compliance journey."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS S3 basics","timeRequired":"PT4M12S","description":"What makes object storage distinct from traditional file storage? In this video, discover the unique advantages offered by Amazon S3 object storage."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Durability and availability","timeRequired":"PT5M53S","description":"Amazon S3 offers a number of different tiers of service that allow you to tune your expectations for price, durability, availability, and retrieval time. In this video, learn how to choose the best option for your needs."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"S3 bucket creation","timeRequired":"PT6M12S","description":"The basic element of storage in Amazon S3 is the \"bucket.\" In this video, learn how to create one in just a few steps, and learn about the various options available to you in the process."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"S3 upload and logging","timeRequired":"PT3M24S","description":"Amazon S3 is filled with powerful and convenient options that just work, such as the ability to log all interactions with a bucket. In this video, learn how to configure logging, upload some data, and observe the results."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"S3 cross-region replication","timeRequired":"PT7M34S","description":"For the most mission-critical workloads, cross-region capabilities are a must, and S3 might be the easiest AWS service on which to enable it. See how in this video."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Set up SNS for event notifications","timeRequired":"PT5M56S","description":"S3 also serves as a trigger for all kinds of downstream automation. In this video, learn how to set up an AWS SNS topic to receive messages when something changes in a bucket."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Set up S3 for event notifications","timeRequired":"PT2M29S","description":"Continuing from the last video, learn how to close the loop by configuring your bucket to notify an SNS topic when data changes in the bucket."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS Glacier and S3 lifecycle rules","timeRequired":"PT6M3S","description":"One of the most powerful features of S3 is its ability to automatically enforce your data lifecycle rules. In this video, learn how to set the criteria for when S3 data converts objects to different storage tiers."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"S3 data lifecycle configuration","timeRequired":"PT5M32S","description":"One of the most powerful features of S3 is its ability to automatically enforce your data lifecycle rules. In this video, learn how to set the criteria for when S3 data converts objects to different storage tiers."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Versioning in S3","timeRequired":"PT1M42S","description":"Object versioning can be a valuable strategy in disaster recovery. In this video, learn how to configure S3 to retain past versions of changed objects."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"S3 teardown","timeRequired":"PT3M8S","description":"To avoid unnecessary charges, clean up the AWS resources you built in this chapter."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Elastic Block Storage","timeRequired":"PT3M45S","description":"Elastic Block Storage is one of AWS's foundational storage services. In this video, learn how EBS works with EC2 to provide storage for your cloud instances."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create an instance with multiple EBS volumes","timeRequired":"PT11M49S","description":"EBS provisioning is quite flexible and straightforward. In this video, learn how to launch an EC2 instance with multiple storage volumes, which you continue to use in the next few videos."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Modify the type and size of an EBS volume","timeRequired":"PT2M42S","description":"Like many things in AWS, a key feature of EBS is scalability. In this video, learn how to resize an EBS volume and update the corresponding EC2 instance to take advantage of the new storage capacity."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Detach and reattach an EBS volume","timeRequired":"PT6M17S","description":"EBS is not only scalable but also reusable. In this video, learn how you can detach a volume from one EC2 instance and mount it on another, retaining all data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"EBS backup, restore, and schedule with CloudWatch","timeRequired":"PT3M5S","description":"Backing up your storage is an essential part of good data management. In this video, learn how to back up EBS—first manually, then on an automated schedule."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Elastic File System","timeRequired":"PT5M42S","description":"Elastic File System provides something that EBS does not—truly networked storage. In this video, find out how EFS allows multiple instances to mount the same volume at the same time."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"EFS demo create EFS","timeRequired":"PT7M5S","description":"See how EFS works in practice. In this video, begin by setting up the instances, security groups, and initial EFS resources."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"EFS demo mount EFS","timeRequired":"PT3M58S","description":"Continuing from the last video, mount the newly created EFS on two different EC2 instances and observe how the two systems are now connected."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"EBS and EFS teardown","timeRequired":"PT3M35S","description":"To avoid unnecessary charges, clean up the AWS resources you built in this section."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Amazon FSx","timeRequired":"PT2M41S","description":"Sometimes you just need to run a file server. In this video, learn how Amazon FSx lets you run popular systems like Windows File Server without having to deal with system provisioning, patching, and many other details of standing up your own file server."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"RDS","timeRequired":"PT8M17S","description":"Relational Database Service lets you hand off the tedious parts of database management to AWS while focusing on getting your important work done. In this video, learn about all the options for standing-up database systems with RDS."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create a MySQL RDS instance","timeRequired":"PT6M26S","description":"In this first demo, go hands-on to create a fresh MySQL instance in RDS. Then, learn how to use this database in subsequent videos to try out some advanced features of the service."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Connect with MySQL Workbench","timeRequired":"PT4M1S","description":"To see the power of RDS in action, you need to get connected! In this video, learn how to access your new MySQL database and seed it with data."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create an Aurora read replica","timeRequired":"PT9M38S","description":"A powerful feature of RDS is its ability to create read replicas automatically, even as live changes hit your primary database. Now that there is data in your database, set up this feature and watch it at work."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"RDS backup and recovery","timeRequired":"PT2M40S","description":"When disaster strikes, RDS backup is here to save the day. In this video, learn how you can restore an RDS backup at a fine-grained point in time."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"RDS teardown","timeRequired":"PT1M55S","description":"To avoid unnecessary charges, clean up the AWS resources you built in this section."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"DynamoDB","timeRequired":"PT6M24S","description":"DynamoDB is the AWS document storage system. In this video, learn how document storage works and how DynamoDB lets you store this kind of data with all the flexibility of an AWS service."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create a DynamoDB table","timeRequired":"PT7M59S","description":"In this video, go hands-on with DynamoDB, creating a table, populating some data, and executing some queries on indices."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Dynamo teardown","timeRequired":"PT27S","description":"To avoid unnecessary charges, clean up the AWS resources you built in this section."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Move data to AWS","timeRequired":"PT2M2S","description":"If you're migrating to AWS from an established project or business, you no doubt have data in another location that needs to get to the cloud. In this video, look at the range of options AWS provides to help make this easy."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Transfer data using the AWS CLI","timeRequired":"PT2M46S","description":"It's time to get behind the terminal! In this video, explore the AWS Command Line Interface and see how some of the most straightforward data transfer options are just a few keystrokes away."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Storage Gateway","timeRequired":"PT5M12S","description":"AWS Storage Gateway lets you access the fundamental availability and durability of object storage through multiple native file system interfaces. In this video, learn about the options for using Storage Gateway to connect systems both in the cloud and on-premises."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Configure File Gateway and shares","timeRequired":"PT7M45S","description":"To get started using S3 as a native file system, you first need to create an AWS File Gateway and corresponding shares. In this video, do just that."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Connect to File Gateway via NFS","timeRequired":"PT4M48S","description":"Continuing from the last video, learn how to mount the newly-created AWS File Gateway via NFS on an EC2 instance."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"File Gateway teardown","timeRequired":"PT2M24S","description":"In this video, clean up resources created during the File Gateway demo, to avoid any unexpected charges."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Transfer data with AWS Snowball","timeRequired":"PT6M38S","description":"When you have so much data to transfer that the internet is just too slow, AWS Snowball provides an option. In this video, learn how these ruggedized storage devices can let you securely ship large amounts of data directly to AWS for optimal \"highway\" bandwidth."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS Database Migration Service","timeRequired":"PT4M48S","description":"Database Migration Service is a highly configurable, powerful tool for piping RDBMS data from one database engine to another. In this video, learn how it can be used to get your data to the cloud efficiently."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"DMS demo: Setup steps","timeRequired":"PT7M58S","description":"In order to demonstrate Database Migration Service, you need to create a new security group and a destination database, and then update the configuration parameters of your source MySQL. Follow along to complete these steps."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"DMS demo: Create replication instance","timeRequired":"PT6M41S","description":"In part one of this demo of DMS, learn how to create a replication task to transfer data between a Postgres and MySQL database."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"DMS demo: Create and execute task","timeRequired":"PT4M57S","description":"Continuing from the last video, learn how to execute the database replication task."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"DMS teardown","timeRequired":"PT2M56S","description":"To avoid unnecessary charges, clean up the AWS resources you built in this section."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS SFTP service","timeRequired":"PT4M28S","description":"Many systems and vendors provide data interfaces that rely on SFTP. In this video, explore how AWS is making it easier to interact with those systems using AWS Transfer for SFTP."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS SFTP prerequisites","timeRequired":"PT6M59S","description":"AWS Transfer for SFTP lets you put an SFTP interface over S3 storage. To try it out, you need an S3 bucket and a new IAM policy that allows the service to access it."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Create an SFTP endpoint","timeRequired":"PT5M53S","description":"AWS Transfer for SFTP lets you build fully managed SFTP endpoints to send and receive data. In this video, configure and construct an SFTP endpoint from scratch."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Send data to S3 using AWS SFTP","timeRequired":"PT2M47S","description":"The fact that AWS Transfer for SFTP is based on S3 makes it yet another good option for migrating data into object-based storage. In this video, use your newly built SFTP endpoint to transfer some data into S3."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS SFTP teardown","timeRequired":"PT1M36S","description":"In this video, clean up resources created during the AWS Transfer for SFTP demo, to avoid any unexpected charges."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS DataSync","timeRequired":"PT2M3S","description":"Many tools offer ways to copy and sync file system data from one place to another. In this video, learn how AWS DataSync makes it easy by integrating directly with destinations in AWS storage offerings."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"Move data with AWS DataSync","timeRequired":"PT5M29S","description":"AWS DataSync makes several common data transfer scenarios easy to set up with minimal—or no—infrastructure. In this video, sync data between S3 and EFS without building any new resources."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS DataSync teardown","timeRequired":"PT1M29S","description":"In this video, clean up resources created during the AWS DataSync demo, to avoid any unexpected charges."},{"@type":"Syllabus","name":"AWS Glue overview","timeRequired":"PT2M31S","description":"AWS Glue is the service that lets AWS users crawl and catalog their data, then use that metadata to automate data integrations with Python.
